-- Spot Electricity Gains on Largest U.S. Grid as Demand Climbs
-- B y   N a u r e e n   S .   M a l i k
-- 2013-07-09T18:41:19Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-09/spot-electricity-gains-on-largest-u-s-grid-as-demand-climbs.html
Spot wholesale power on the 13-state
eastern U.S. grid operated by PJM Interconnection LLC gained as
demand topped forecasts.  Electricity consumption was 130,886 megawatts at 1:25 p.m.,
1.7 percent higher than the day-ahead outlook for the hour,
PJM’s website showed. The high in  Washington  may be 89 degrees
Fahrenheit (25 Celsius), in line with the seasonal norm, up from
a reading of 1 below normal of 87 yesterday, according to
AccuWeather Inc. in  State College ,  Pennsylvania .  Spot power at PJM’s benchmark  Western hub , which includes
prices from Washington to Erie, Pennsylvania, rose $5.42, or 11
percent, to $55.03 a megawatt-hour during the hour ended at 1
p.m., grid data compiled by Bloomberg showed. Yesterday’s day-ahead outlook for the hour was $43.33.  On-peak power at the Western hub is trading at an average
 discount  versus the Eastern hub, which includes prices from New
Jersey to  Virginia , of $2.64 a megawatt-hour as of 1 p.m.,
versus $2.25 yesterday. On-peak hours are Monday through Friday
7 a.m. to 11 p.m.  PJM cut its  peak-demand outlook  for today to 137,272
megawatts during the hour ended at 6 p.m. from 139,273 megawatts
in a forecast released late yesterday.  Northeast power prices fell as demand slumped in  New York 
and consumers in the six New England states were using less
power than the region’s grid operated had projected.  New York City electricity dropped $26.71, or 30 percent, to
$63.15 a megawatt-hour in the hour ended at 1 p.m. from a day
earlier while Boston fell $33.25, or 40 percent, to $50.15.  On-peak power for New York was fetching a premium of $5.41
versus Boston, down from yesterday’s average of $122.46. The
premium for New York power Public Service Enterprise Group
Inc.’s northern  New Jersey  utility territory, a part of the PJM
grid, narrowed to 94 cents from $134.71 yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
